 analysis of the Marsham phenological record, 1736-1947 (1995) Journal of Ecology, 83, pp. 321-329; Sparks, T.H., Huber, K., Croxton, P.J., Plant development scores from fixed-date photographs: The influence of weather variables and recorder experience (2006) International Journal of Biometeorology, 50, pp. 275-279; Sparks, T.H., Jeffree, E.P., Jeffree, C.E., An examination of the relationship between flowering times and temperature at the national scale using long-term phenological records from the UK (2000) International Journal of Biometeorology, 44, pp. 82-87; Trimble, S.W., Crosson, P., U.S. soil erosion rates - Myth and reality (2000) Science, 289, pp. 248-250; Visser, M.E., Both, C., Shifts in phenology due to global climate change: The need for a yardstick (2005) Proceedings of the Royal Society of London, B, Biological Sciences, 272, pp. 2561-2569; Walther, G.R., Post, E., Convey, P., Menzel, A., Parmesan, C., Beebee, T.J.C., Fromentin, J.M., Bairlein, F., Ecological responses to recent climate change (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 389-395; White, M.A., Nemani, A.R., Canopy duration has little influence on annual carbon storage in the deciduous broad leaf forest (2003) Global Change Biology, 9, pp. 967-972","Miller-Rushing, A.J.; Department of Biology, Boston University, Boston, MA 02215, United States; email: ajmr@bu.edu",,,,,,,,00029122,,AJBOA,,"English","Am. J. Bot.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-33751211895
